\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Short answer: 
\f1\b yes\'97both patterns exist, but in practice a single \'93delegate\'94 (entity) usually has 
\f2\i multiple delegation agreements or scoped addenda
\f1\i0  rather than one monolithic agreement.
\f0\b0 \
The nuance comes down to how 
\f1\b functions, lines of business, and risk are structured
\f0\b0 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa375\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs56 \cf0 \strokec2 \uc0\u55358 \u56809  1) A \'93delegate\'94 is usually an organization, not an individual\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs28 \cf0 First, a quick clarification that matters for your data model:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The 
\f1\b \'93delegate\'94 is almost never an individual provider
\f0\b0 \
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 It\'92s typically a 
\f1\b legal entity
\f0\b0 :\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Medical group\
\ls1\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 IPA\
\ls1\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Health system\
\ls1\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Vendor (e.g., CVO, UM vendor)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \uc0\u10145 \u65039  Individual providers sit 
\f3\i under
\f0\i0  that entity\
This distinction is important because 
\f1\b agreements are executed at the entity level
\f0\b0 , not per individual provider.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa375\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs56 \cf0 \strokec2 \uc0\u55357 \u56576  2) Can one delegate have multiple delegation agreements?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa327\partightenfactor0

\fs32\fsmilli16380 \cf0 \uc0\u9989  Yes \'97 and this is very common\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs28 \cf0 A single delegate entity can have 
\f1\b multiple active agreements simultaneously
\f0\b0 , typically segmented by:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa348\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs42 \cf0 \strokec2 A. Function (most common driver)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs28 \cf0 Each delegated function is often governed separately.\
Example:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Agreement 1 \uc0\u8594  Utilization Management (UM)\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Agreement 2 \uc0\u8594  Credentialing\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Agreement 3 \uc0\u8594  Claims processing (less common but possible)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Why:\
